Definition 2.11 [22] A monad on a category C is a triple $(T,\eta,\_^{\dagger})$ consisting of a map $T$ from objects $X$ of C to objects $TX$ of C, a collection $\eta=(\eta_{X})_{X}$ of morphisms $\eta_{X}\colon X\to TX$, one for each object $X$ of C, and a so-called extension operation $\_^{\dagger}$ that maps every morphism $f\colon X\to TY$ to $f^{\dagger}\colon TX\to TY$ such that: 1. $\eta_{X}^{\dagger}=\mathrm{id}_{TX}$; 2. for every morphism $f\colon X\to TY$, $f^{\dagger}\circ\eta_{X}=f$; 3. for all morphisms $f\colon X\to TY$ and $g\colon Y\to TZ$, $g^{\dagger}\circ f^{\dagger}=(g^{\dagger}\circ f)^{\dagger}$.
Definition 4.1 Let $C$ be a semitopological cone, and $\nu$ be a continuous valuation on $C$. A barycentre of $\nu$ is any point $b_{\nu}\in C$ such that, for every linear lower semi-continuous map $\Lambda\colon C\to\overline{\mathbb{R}}_{+}$, $\Lambda(b_{\nu})=\int\Lambda~{}d\nu$.
Definition 5. A $C$-monomial $G$-poset is a pair $(X,\mathfrak{l})$ consisting of a $G$-poset $X$ and a functor $\mathfrak{l}:\widehat{X}\rightarrow\bullet_{C}$.
Definition 1. A $C$-monomial $G$-set is a pair $(X,\mathfrak{l})$ consisting of a finite $G$-set $X$ and a functor $\mathfrak{l}:\widehat{X}\rightarrow\bullet_{C}$.
Definition 21. The above construction $T_{U,\lambda}:(X,\mathfrak{l})\mapsto\big{(}t_{U,\lambda}(X,\mathfrak{l}),% \mathfrak{L}_{U,\lambda}\big{)}$ is called the generalized tensor induction for $C$-monomial $G$-posets, associated to $(U,\lambda)$.
Definition 3.15. (CassidyClassification, , page 222) A connected differential algebraic group is called simple if it is non-commutative and has no nontrivial connected normal differential algebraic subgroups.
Definition 3.1. A neutral differential Tannakian category over a differential field $(\operatorname{\bf k},\Delta=\{\partial_{1},\ldots,\partial_{m}\})$ is a rigid tensor abelian category $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ with $\operatorname{\mathrm{E}nd}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}({\mathbbm{1}})=% \operatorname{\bf k}$, where ${\mathbbm{1}}$ is the unit object in $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, supplied with the following data: 1. functors $\operatorname{\mathrm{F}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}},i}:\operatorname{% \mathcal{C}}\to\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, $1\leqslant i\leqslant m$, with exact sequences of functors $\begin{CD}0@>{}>{}>\operatorname{\mathrm{i}d}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}@>{% \iota_{i}}>{}>\operatorname{\mathrm{F}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}},i}@>{\pi_{% i}}>{}>\operatorname{\mathrm{i}d}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}@>{}>{}>0,\end{CD}$ that is, a functorial exact sequence $\begin{CD}0@>{}>{}>X@>{\iota_{X,i}}>{}>\operatorname{\mathrm{F}}_{% \operatorname{\mathcal{C}},i}(X)@>{\pi_{X,i}}>{}>X@>{}>{}>0\end{CD}$ for any object $X$ in $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, such that the differential structure induced by all the $\operatorname{\mathrm{F}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}},i}$â€™s on $\operatorname{\bf k}$ coincides with the given $\Delta$ (see (difftann, , Lemma 7) and (Moshe, , Section 5.2.2)) 2. functorial isomorphisms $S_{i,j}:\operatorname{\mathrm{F}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}},i}(\operatorname% {\mathrm{F}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}},j}(X))\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{% \longrightarrow}}\operatorname{\mathrm{F}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}},j}(% \operatorname{\mathrm{F}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}},i}(X))$ for all $1\leqslant i,j\leqslant m$ and $X\in{\mathrm{O}b}(\operatorname{\mathcal{C}})$; 3. functorial morphisms $T_{X,Y,i}:\operatorname{\mathrm{F}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}},i}(X\otimes Y)% \to\operatorname{\mathrm{F}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}},i}(X)\otimes% \operatorname{\mathrm{F}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}},i}(Y)$ for all objects $X$ and $Y$ in $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ and $1\leqslant i\leqslant m$; 4. an exact tensor $k$-linear functor $\omega:\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}\to\operatorname{\bf Vect}_{\operatorname{\bf k}}$ with functorial isomorphisms of $\operatorname{\bf k}$-vector spaces $\Gamma_{X,i}:\omega(\operatorname{\mathrm{F}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}},i}(X% ))\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\longrightarrow}}F_{i}(\omega(X))$ for any object $X$ in $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, such that $\Gamma$ sends exact sequences of type (3) to exact sequences of type (1), isomorphisms of type (4) to isomorphisms of type (2), and morphisms of type (5) to the morphisms of the following type: $T_{U,V,i}:F_{i}(U\otimes_{\operatorname{\bf k}}V)\to F_{i}(U)\otimes_{% \operatorname{\bf k}}F_{i}(V)$ given by the formula $\displaystyle 1\otimes(u\otimes v)$ $\displaystyle\mapsto(1\otimes u)\otimes(1\otimes v),$ $\displaystyle\partial_{i}\otimes(u\otimes v)$ $\displaystyle\mapsto(\partial_{i}\otimes u)\otimes(1\otimes v)+(1\otimes u)% \otimes(\partial_{i}\otimes v),$ for all $u\in U$, $v\in V$, and $1\leqslant i\leqslant m$. Such a functor $\omega$ is called a differential fibre functor.
Definition 3.6. Such $G$ is called a unipotent LDAG.
Definition 4.1. A group $\Gamma$ is a product of its subgroups $M$ and $N$ if the product morphism $M\times N\to\Gamma$ is surjective and $mn=nm$ for all $m\in M$, $n\in N$. In this case, we write $\Gamma=MN.$ If $|M\cap N|<\infty$, we say that $\Gamma$ is an almost direct product of $M$ and $N$, and we write $\Gamma=M\cdot N.$
Definition 3.12. A linear differential algebraic group $G$ is called reductive if its unipotent radical is trivial, that is, $\operatorname{R_{u}}(G)=\{e\}$.
Definition 2.1. For a differential field extension $K\supset\operatorname{\bf k}$, a Kolchin closed subset $W(K)$ of $K^{n}$ over $\operatorname{\bf k}$ is the set of common zeroes of a system of differential algebraic equations with coefficients in $\operatorname{\bf k},$ that is, for $f_{1},\ldots,f_{k}\in\operatorname{\bf k}\{Y\}$ we define $W(K)=\left\{a\in K^{n}\>|\>f_{1}(a)=\ldots=f_{k}(a)=0\right\}.$
Definition 3.16. (CassidyClassification, , page 222) A connected differential algebraic group is called semisimple if it has no nontrivial connected normal commutative differential algebraic subgroups.
Definition 3.11. The subgroup $\operatorname{R_{u}}(G)$ is called the unipotent radical of $G$.
Definition 4.4. A LDAG $G\subset{\bf GL}_{n}(\operatorname{\mathcal{U}})$ is called constant-dense, if there is a LAG $G_{0}\subset{\bf GL}_{n}({\rm C})$ such that $G_{0}\subset G\subset\overline{G_{0}}.$
Definition 2.3. CassidyRep Let $G$ be a LDAG. A differential polynomial group homomorphism $\rho:G\to{\bf GL}(V)$ is called a differential representation of $G$, where $V$ is a finite dimensional vector space over $\operatorname{\bf k}$. Such a space is called a $G$-module. As usual, morphisms between $G$-modules are $\operatorname{\bf k}$-linear maps that are $G$-equivariant. The category of differential representations of $G$ is denoted by $\operatorname{\bf Rep}_{G}$.
Definition 2.2. (Cassidy, , Chapter II, Section 1, page 905) A linear differential algebraic group is a Kolchin closed subgroup $G$ of ${\bf GL}_{n}(\operatorname{\mathcal{U}}),$ that is, an intersection of a Kolchin closed subset of $\operatorname{\mathcal{U}}^{n^{2}}$ with ${\bf GL}_{n}(\operatorname{\mathcal{U}})$, which is closed under the group operations.
Definition 2.2. Let $\alpha$ be a regular cardinal. A morphism $X\to Y$ in an arbitrary category is called (1) $\alpha$-pure monomorphism, if it is an $\alpha$-filtered colimit of split monomorphisms, (2) $\alpha$-pure epimorphism, if it is an $\alpha$-filtered colimit of split epimorphisms, and (3) $\alpha$-terminal if for every factorisation $X\to X^{\prime}\to Y$ the morphism $X\to X^{\prime}$ is invertible if it is an $\alpha$-pure epimorphism.
Definition 10 Let $\mathbf{M}=(M,m,u)$ be a monad on $Set$. A pair of $Set$-endofunctors $(T,H)$ such that $HM\cong MT$ is called an $\mathbf{M}$-commuting pair.
Definition 1.4. A class $\mathcal{F}$ of objects in $\mathcal{G}$ is called deconstructible if there is a set $\mathcal{S}$ such that $\mathcal{F}=\hbox{\rm Filt-}{\mathcal{S}}$.
Definition 1.3. Let $\mathcal{S}$ be a class of objects of $\mathcal{G}$. An object $X\in\mathcal{G}$ is called $\mathcal{S}$-filtered if there exists a well-ordered direct system $(X_{\alpha},i_{\alpha\beta}\mid\alpha<\beta\leq\sigma)$ indexed by an ordinal number $\sigma$ such that (1) $X_{0}=0$ and $X_{\sigma}=X$, (2) for each limit ordinal $\mu\leq\sigma$, the colimit of the subsystem $(X_{\alpha},i_{\alpha\beta}\mid\alpha<\beta<\mu)$ is precisely $X_{\mu}$, the colimit morphisms being $i_{\alpha\mu}:X_{\alpha}\to X_{\mu}$, (3) $i_{\alpha\beta}:X_{\alpha}\to X_{\beta}$ is a monomorphism in $\mathcal{G}$ for each $\alpha<\beta\leq\sigma$, (4) $\operatorname{Coker}i_{\alpha,\alpha+1}\in\mathcal{S}$ for each $\alpha<\sigma$. The direct system $(X_{\alpha},i_{\alpha\beta})$ is then called an $\mathcal{S}$-filtration of $X$. The class of all $\mathcal{S}$-filtered objects in $\mathcal{G}$ is denoted by $\hbox{\rm Filt-}{\mathcal{S}}$.
Definition 2.6. Let $\mathcal{F}\subseteq\mathcal{G}$ be a class of objects and $\kappa$ a regular cardinal. Then $\mathcal{F}$ is said to be a $\kappa$-Kaplansky class if for any $F\in\mathcal{F}$ and a $<\kappa$-generated subobject $X\subseteq F$, there exists a $<\kappa$-presentable subobject $Y$ of $F$ such that $X\subseteq Y\subseteq F$ and $Y,F/Y\in\mathcal{F}$. We say that $\mathcal{F}$ is a Kaplansky class if it is $\kappa$-Kaplansky for some regular cardinal $\kappa$.
