Definition 2.4. A functor $F:\mathcal{K}\to\mathcal{L}$ will be called well $\lambda$-accessible if $\mathcal{K}$ and $\mathcal{L}$ are well $\lambda$-accessible categories and $F$ preserves $\lambda$-directed colimits and $\mu$-presentable objects for each $\lambda\leq\mu$. $F$ is called well accessible if it is well $\lambda$-accessible for some regular cardinal $\lambda$.
Definition 2.1. We say that a category $\mathcal{K}$ is well $\lambda$-accessible if it is $\mu$-accessible for each regular cardinal $\lambda\leq\mu$. $\mathcal{K}$ is well accessible if it is well $\lambda$-accessible for some regular cardinal $\lambda$.
Definition 2.6. We say that a functor $F:\mathcal{K}\to\mathcal{L}$ reflects split epimorphisms if $f$ is a split epimorphism whenever $F(f)$ is a split epimorphism.
