Definition 3.1. A sequence of objects $(e_{1},\dots,e_{n})$ is called numerically semiorthonormal if $\chi(e_{i},e_{i})=1$ and $\chi(e_{j},e_{i})=0$ whenever $j>i$. It is called a numerically semiorthonormal basis if moreover $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$ is a basis of $\mathrm{K}_{0}(Z)/(\mathrm{tors})$. This is equivalent to $n=\mathrm{rk}(\mathrm{K}_{0}(Z)/(\mathrm{tors}))$.
Definition 2.3. A semiorthogonal decomposition $\mathcal{T}=\langle\mathcal{S}_{1},\dots,\mathcal{S}_{n}\rangle$ is called maximal if each $\mathcal{S}_{i}$ does not have any nontrivial semiorthogonal decompositions. The category $\mathcal{T}$ satisfies the Jordan-HÃ¶lder property if, firstly, $\mathcal{T}$ satisfies the Noetherian property, and, secondly, if $\mathcal{T}=\langle\mathcal{S}_{1},\dots,\mathcal{S}_{n}\rangle$ and $\mathcal{T}=\langle\mathcal{U}_{1},\dots,\mathcal{U}_{m}\rangle$ are two maximal semiorthogonal decompositions, then $m=n$ and there exists a bijection $\sigma\colon\{1,\dots,n\}\xymatrix@1@=15pt{\ar[r]&}\{1,\dots,m\}$ such that $\mathcal{S}_{i}$ is equivalent to $\mathcal{U}_{\sigma(i)}$.
Definition 2.1. A subcategory $\mathcal{S}\subset\mathcal{T}$ is called admissible if the inclusion functor has a left and right adjoint. A sequence of admissible subcategories $(\mathcal{S}_{1},\dots,\mathcal{S}_{n})$ of $\mathcal{T}$ is called a semiorthogonal decomposition of $\mathcal{T}$ if $\mathrm{Hom}(S_{j},S_{i})=0$ for all objects $S_{j}\in\mathcal{S}_{j}$, $S_{i}\in\mathcal{S}_{i}$ with $j>i$, and, moreover, the subcategories $\mathcal{S}_{i}$ generate $\mathcal{T}$ in the sense that the smallest triangulated subcategory containing all of them is equivalent to $\mathcal{T}$. One writes $\mathcal{T}=\langle\mathcal{S}_{1},\dots,\mathcal{S}_{n}\rangle.$
Definition 2.5. Let $\mathfrak{D}$ be a maximal semiorthogonal decomposition of $\mathcal{T}=\mathrm{D}^{b}(X)$ where $X$ is a smooth projective variety of dimension $n$: $\mathcal{T}=\langle\mathcal{S}_{1},\dots,\mathcal{S}_{n}\rangle.$ The Clemens-Griffiths component $\mathrm{CG}(\mathfrak{D})$ of $\mathfrak{D}$ is defined as the smallest triangulated subcategory of $\mathcal{T}$ which contains all those $\mathcal{S}_{i}$ with $\mathrm{ess.dim}(\mathcal{S}_{i})\geq n-1$.
Definition 3.9. Consider the lattice $\Lambda:=\left\{x+y_{0}h+y_{1}e_{1}+\dots+y_{8}e_{8}+\frac{1}{2}zp\right\}% \subset\mathrm{CH}^{*}(S)[1/2]$ where $(x,y_{0},y_{1},\dots,y_{8},z)\in\mathbb{Z}^{11}$ and $p$ is the class of a point. We set $v=(x,y,z)$, where $y=y_{0}h+y_{1}e_{1}+\dots+y_{8}e_{8}.$
Definition 2.2. The category $\mathcal{T}$ satisfies the Noetherian property if every increasing sequence $\mathcal{S}_{1}\subset\mathcal{S}_{2}\subset\dots$ of admissible subcategories becomes stationary.
Definition 2.6. An object $E\in\mathrm{D}^{b}(X)$ is called exceptional if $\mathrm{RHom}^{\bullet}(E,E)\simeq\mathbb{C}$. An exceptional sequence is a sequence of exceptional objects $(E_{1},\dots,E_{m})$ with $\mathrm{RHom}^{\bullet}(E_{j},E_{i})=0$ for $j>i$. The sequence is called unextendable if there does not exist an exceptional object $F$ in $\mathrm{D}^{b}(X)$ such that $(E_{1},\dots,E_{m},F)$ is an exceptional sequence.
Definition 2.4. The essential dimension $\mathrm{ess.dim}(\mathcal{T})$ of $\mathcal{T}$ is the minimum integer $n$ such that there exists a fully faithful embedding $\mathcal{T}\xymatrix@1@=15pt{\ar@{{}^{(}->}[r]&}\mathrm{D}^{b}(X)$ with admissible image, where $X$ is a smooth projective variety of dimension $n$. We set $\mathrm{ess.dim}(\mathcal{T})=\infty$ if no such integer exists.
Definition 4.6. A ringed category is a pair $(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{O})$ where $\mathcal{X}$ is a category with finite products and $\mathcal{O}$ is a ring object in $\mathcal{X}$; we refer to $\mathcal{O}$ as the structure ring object of $(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{O})$. A morphism of ringed categories $(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{O}_{\mathcal{X}})\to(\mathcal{Y},\mathcal{O}_{\mathcal{Y% }})$ is a pair $(f_{*},\underline{f})$ where $f_{*}\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{Y}$ is a functor in $\mathsf{fpCat}$ and $\underline{f}\colon\mathcal{O}_{\mathcal{Y}}\to f_{*}\mathcal{O}_{\mathcal{X}}$ is a morphism in $\mathsf{RingObj}(\mathcal{Y})$. Given morphisms $(f_{*},\underline{f})\colon(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{O}_{\mathcal{X}})\to(\mathcal% {Y},\mathcal{O}_{\mathcal{Y}})$ and $(g_{*},\underline{g})\colon(\mathcal{Y},\mathcal{O}_{Y})\to(\mathcal{Z},% \mathcal{O}_{\mathcal{Z}})$, we define their composite to be the morphism $(g_{*},\underline{g})\circ(f_{*},\underline{f})=(g_{*}\circ f_{*},\underline{g% }\circ g_{*}(\underline{f})).$ This operation is readily seen to be associative. The category $\mathsf{RingedCat}$ has ringed categories for objects, with morphisms and composition rule as above. The assignment $(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{O}_{\mathcal{X}})\mapsto\Gamma(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{O}_{% X})$ defines a functor $\Gamma\colon\mathsf{RingedCat}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathsf{Ring}$, which we also refer to as the global sections functor.
